{"title":"M1 Mac users are reporting excessive SSD wear and tear","link":"https://www.macworld.com/article/3609096/m1-macbook-mac-mini-ssd-read-write-data-overuse.html#tk.rss_all","date":1614104700000,"content":"<div id=\"readability-page-1\" class=\"page\"><section role=\"main\" id=\"page-wrapper\"><article itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/NewsArticle\"><meta itemprop=\"keywords\" content=\"macs,  \"><header><ins data-ad-client=\"ca-pub-4268075595326305\" data-ad-slot=\"9945794902\" data-ad-format=\"link\" data-adsbygoogle-status=\"done\"><ins id=\"aswift_0_expand\" tabindex=\"0\" title=\"Advertisement\" aria-label=\"Advertisement\"><ins id=\"aswift_0_anchor\"></ins></ins></ins><section><h3 itemprop=\"description\">That’s a problem because it could lead to worn-out drives.</h3></section><div><p>Senior Editor, <span itemprop=\"publisher\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Organization\"><span itemprop=\"name\">Macworld</span><meta itemprop=\"url\" content=\"https://www.macworld.com\"><meta itemprop=\"logo\" content=\"https://alt.idgesg.net/images/furniture/macworld/MW_logo_300x300.png\"></span><span>|</span> <span itemprop=\"datePublished\" content=\"2021-02-23T10:25-0800\"><span>Feb 23, 2021 10:25 am PST</span></span></p></div></header><div><div><figure itemprop=\"image\" itemscope=\"\" itemtype=\"http://schema.org/ImageObject\"><meta itemprop=\"representativeOfPage\" content=\"1\"><meta itemprop=\"height\" content=\"800\"><meta itemprop=\"width\" content=\"1200\"><meta itemprop=\"url\" content=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2020/11/13in-m1-mbp-desk-100866774-large.jpg\"><img data-original=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2020/11/13in-m1-mbp-desk-100866774-large.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"13in m1 mbp desk\" itemprop=\"contentUrl\" src=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2020/11/13in-m1-mbp-desk-100866774-large.jpg\"><figcaption><span itemprop=\"copyrightHolder\">IDG</span></figcaption></figure></div></div><section><div id=\"drr-container\" itemprop=\"articleBody\"><p>If you have a new M1 Mac, you probably think it's going to last for years and years, but some new troubling data suggests that might not be the case. More than a few users are reporting&nbsp;that SSDs on Apple’s M1 Macs are possibly being overused by the system, which could cause them to wear out earlier than usual.</p><p>Twitter user <a href=\"https://twitter.com/never_released/status/1360657594197671941\" rel=\"nofollow\">@never_released</a> started a thread that shows a report of an M1 Mac with very high write counts for a computer that’s only two months old. That led other M1 owners to run the same report, and many have also found excessive usage, including Macworld columnist <a href=\"https://twitter.com/i/web/status/1364248848730882053\" rel=\"nofollow\">Dan Moren</a>.</p><figure><img alt=\"longhorn twitter m1 mac ssd\" width=\"1200\" height=\"898\" data-imageid=\"100878438\" data-license=\"Supplied Art\" data-original=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2021/02/longhorn-twitter-m1-mac-ssd-100878438-large.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2021/02/longhorn-twitter-m1-mac-ssd-100878438-large.jpg\"> <small><a href=\"https://twitter.com/never_released/status/1360657594197671941\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter</a></small></figure><figure><img alt=\"dmoren twitter m1 mac ssd\" width=\"1200\" height=\"1207\" data-imageid=\"100878439\" data-license=\"Supplied Art\" data-original=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2021/02/dmoren-twitter-m1-mac-ssd-100878439-large.jpg\" loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://images.idgesg.net/images/article/2021/02/dmoren-twitter-m1-mac-ssd-100878439-large.jpg\"> <small><a href=\"https://twitter.com/i/web/status/1364248848730882053\" rel=\"noopener nofollow\" target=\"_blank\">Twitter</a></small></figure><p>SSDs are favored over traditional hard drives because they’re much faster, but SSDs do have a limited lifespan. An SSD wears down every time you write to it, and eventually, the drive will have problems and will likely need to be replaced. However, this is supposed to take several years to happen, and macOS spreads the writing across an SSD to extend its life. Based on these readings, that might happen a lot sooner than expected.</p><p>It’s possible that there’s an error in the reporting tool, but it’s also possible macOS is doing something to the SSD to cause these spikes. If so, it's concerning because the SSD drives on these new Mac are not user-serviceable and costs hundreds of dollars to replace.</p><div><p><img onclick=\"jwplayer('bottomRightPlayer').remove(); this.style.display = 'none';\" id=\"jw-standalone-close-button\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\"></p><div id=\"bottomRightPlayer\" tabindex=\"0\" aria-label=\"Video Player\" role=\"application\" aria-describedby=\"jw-shortcuts-tooltip-explanation\"><div dir=\"auto\"><p>MacBook Buying Guide 2020</p></div><p><span aria-live=\"assertive\"></span><span aria-live=\"assertive\">Volume 0%</span></p></div></div><p>We’ve reached out to Apple for comment and will update this story if we hear back.</p><div><p>Note: When you purchase something after clicking links in our articles, we may earn a small commission. Read our <a href=\"https://www.macworld.com/about/affiliates.html\">affiliate link policy</a> for more details.</p></div></div><div><p>Roman has covered technology since the early 1990s. His career started at MacUser, and he's worked for MacAddict, Mac|Life, and TechTV.</p></div></section></article></section></div>","author":"Roman Loyola","siteTitle":"Macworld","siteHash":"37e84dd5a21fa961d6d6630e269546024dbb7741b2e2fadbe74f47383c70dfbb","entryHash":"7677285529283927e00c5b1645282e0f65e1725590627476da0fee9864182acb","category":"Apple"}